children.label: arrayOfStrings
description:
Read a string flag that supports multiple instances into an array of strings. If the
flag is only passed once an array with a single item will be returned. If the flag is not
passed then undefined will be returned.

children.label: requiredArrayOfStrings
description:
Same as #arrayOfStrings() except when the flag is not passed a "flag error" is thrown telling
the user that the flag is required and shows them the help text.

children.label: string
description:
Read the value of a string flag. If the flag is passed multiple times the last value is returned. If
the flag is not passed then undefined is returned.

children.label: enum
description:
Same as #string() except when the flag is passed it is validated against a list
of valid values
signature: <T extends string>(key: string, values: readonly T[]) => T | undefined

children.label: requiredString
description:
Same as #string() except when a flag is not passed a "flag error" is thrown telling the user
that the flag is required and shows them the help text.

children.label: path
description:
Same as #string(), except that when there is a value for the string it is resolved to an
absolute path based on the current working directory

children.label: requiredPath
description:
Same as #requiredString() except that values are converted to absolute paths based on the
current working directory

children.label: arrayOfPaths
description:
Same as #arrayOfStrings(), except that when there are values they are resolved to
absolute paths based on the current working directory

children.label: requiredArrayOfPaths
description:
Same as #requiredArrayOfStrings(), except that values are resolved to absolute paths
based on the current working directory

children.label: number
description:
Parsed the provided flag as a number, if the value does not parse to a valid number
using Number.parseFloat() then a "flag error" is thrown. If the flag is not passed
undefined is returned.

children.label: requiredNumber
description: Same as #number() except that when the flag is missing a "flag error" is thrown

children.label: boolean
description:
Read a boolean flag value, if the flag is properly defined as a "boolean" in the run options
then the value will always be a boolean, defaulting to `false`, so there is no need for an
optional/requiredBoolean() method.

children.label: getPositionals
description:
Get the positional arguments passed, includes any values that are not associated with
a specific --flag

children.label: getUnused
description:
Returns all of the unused flags. When a flag is read via any of the key-specific methods
the key is marked as "used" and this method will return a map of just the flags which
have not been used yet (excluding the default flags like --debug, --verbose, and --help)

children.label: getUsed
description:
Returns all of the used flags. When a flag is read via any of the key-specific methods
the key is marked as "used" and from then on this method will return a map including that
and any other key used by these methods.

children.label: log
signature: { defaultLevel?: "info" | "error" | "success" | "warning" | "debug" | "verbose" | "silent" | undefined; context?: string | undefined; } | undefined

children.label: log
signature: { defaultLevel?: "info" | "error" | "success" | "warning" | "debug" | "verbose" | "silent" | undefined; context?: string | undefined; } | undefined

misc.label: BaseFlags
description:
Base variant of Flags that does not automatically set unspecified
flags `([key:string]: ...)`
signature: { verbose: boolean; quiet: boolean; silent: boolean; debug: boolean; help: boolean; _: string[]; unexpected: string[]; } & TExtraFlags

misc.label: CleanupTask
description:
A function which will be called when the CLI is torn-down which should
quickly cleanup whatever it needs.

misc.label: Flags
signature: { verbose: boolean; quiet: boolean; silent: boolean; debug: boolean; help: boolean; _: string[]; unexpected: string[]; } & UnspecifiedFlags

misc.label: FlagsOf
description:
Infer the type of Flags from FlagOptions. Inference only kicks in when
either `string` or `boolean` consists of string literals (which only
is the case when the flag options are tagged with the `as const` modifier.)
Otherwise the type we create is too specific and we'd have to use `as const`
everywhere.
signature: (IsStringLiteral<TFlagOptions["string"]> extends false | null | undefined ? IsStringLiteral<TFlagOptions["boolean"]> extends false | null | undefined ? false : IsStringLiteral<TFlagOptions["boolean"]> : IsStringLiteral<TFlagOptions["string"]>) extends true ?

<(true extends TFlagOptions["allowUnexpected"] ? UnspecifiedFlags : {}) & (TFlagOptions["string"] extends string[] ? FlagsToObj<TFlagOptions["string"], string> : {}) & (TFlagOptions["boolean"] extends string[] ? FlagsToObj<TFlagOptions["boolean"], boolean> : {})> :
